---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Strategy Library"
  description="Reference execution configurations for n0brains signals — backtested on real 1-minute candles across Binance, Bybit, and Coinbase. Analytical examples, not advice."
>
  <section class="docs-page">
    <h1>Strategy Library</h1>
    <p class="docs-subtitle">Reference execution configurations for n0brains signals &middot; Backtested on real 1-minute candles &middot; Reproducible</p>

    <div class="card legal-card">
      <h2>This is research, not advice.</h2>
      <p>
        These are <strong>reference execution examples</strong> — researched configurations we ran
        against historical 1-minute price candles from Binance, Bybit, and Coinbase to study how
        n0brains signals would have performed under different exit rules. They are
        <strong>not</strong> recommendations to enter, exit, hold, or size a trade.
      </p>
      <p>
        Past simulated performance does not guarantee future results. Slippage, fees, fills, and
        market conditions vary. You are solely responsible for every trading decision you make
        and for any profits or losses that result. See the full
        <a href="/terms">terms of service</a> §8.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2 id="methodology">Methodology</h2>
      <p>
        Every configuration in this library was simulated against the actual 1-minute close
        prices on three major exchanges (Binance perp, Bybit perp, Coinbase spot) for the last
        30 days of signals. Each signal was paper-traded with:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Fixed $100 position size</li>
        <li>Taker fee: 4.5 bps round-trip (Hyperliquid taker rate; adjust for your venue)</li>
        <li>Slippage: 2 bps entry + 2 bps exit</li>
        <li>Per-signal-type score percentile gate (default top 30% of recent signals)</li>
        <li>Direction-corrected return path (bullish positive on price up; bearish positive on price down)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Results below are aggregated across all three exchanges where the asset trades. Per-type
        sharpe (return / stdev) is reported alongside total PnL to show risk-adjusted performance,
        not just raw $ won.
      </p>
      <p>
        Reproducible: <code>/home/oba/paper-trader/sweep.py</code> and <code>exotic_sweep.py</code>
        in our repo. Live ongoing forward-test at <a href="/proof">/proof</a>.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2 id="per-type">Per-signal-type winning configurations</h2>
      <p>
        We searched 1,728 parameter combinations (SL × TP × horizon × trailing × score
        percentile) per signal_type against real 1-minute candles. Each type has its own
        optimal exit rule — no single config wins across all types. The table below shows
        the empirical best per type. Tradeable types are highlighted; types where no config
        flips positive are listed below as intel-only.
      </p>
      <table class="strat-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Type</th><th>SL</th><th>TP</th><th>Horizon</th><th>Trail</th><th>n</th><th>Win %</th><th>Avg net</th><th>Total $</th><th>Sharpe</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="row-best">
            <td><code>listing</code></td>
            <td>none</td><td>5%</td><td>1h</td><td>—</td>
            <td>156</td><td>92.3%</td><td>+10.5%</td><td>+$1639</td><td>1.61</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="row-best">
            <td><code>sentiment</code></td>
            <td>5%</td><td>12%</td><td>24h</td><td>3%</td>
            <td>715</td><td>79.2%</td><td>+2.99%</td><td>+$2137</td><td>0.70</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="row-best">
            <td><code>macro_pulse</code></td>
            <td>2%</td><td>5%</td><td>24h</td><td>—</td>
            <td>56</td><td>60.7%</td><td>+0.82%</td><td>+$46</td><td>0.41</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="row-best">
            <td><code>hack</code></td>
            <td>none</td><td>20%</td><td>72h</td><td>—</td>
            <td>117</td><td>42.7%</td><td>+2.87%</td><td>+$336</td><td>0.32</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="row-best">
            <td><code>whale</code></td>
            <td>1%</td><td>8%</td><td>24h</td><td>—</td>
            <td>366</td><td>32.8%</td><td>+0.85%</td><td>+$313</td><td>0.24</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p class="meta">
        30 days of binance 1-minute candles. Score-percentile gate per type (sentiment p50,
        whale p70, etc — see the methodology section). Fee 4.5 bps round-trip, slippage 2 bps
        each side. Sharpe is per-trade return / per-trade stdev.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2 id="type-detail">Detail on each tradeable type</h2>
      <h3><code>listing</code> &middot; Strongest edge in the feed</h3>
      <p>
        New listing announcements (CEX listings, ETF approvals, etc) trigger immediate buying
        pressure that spikes price within minutes. Best setup: <strong>no stop, take profit at
        +5%, exit at 1 hour</strong>. 92% win rate, sharpe 1.61. Pump-and-fade nature — get out
        fast on the spike, don't hold for more.
      </p>

      <h3><code>sentiment</code> &middot; Largest tradeable inventory</h3>
      <p>
        Aggregated cross-source narrative and social momentum. Best setup: <strong>SL 5%,
        TP 12%, 24-hour horizon, plus a 3% trailing stop</strong> that locks profits once
        the trade moves favorably. 79% win, sharpe 0.70 over 715 trades. The trailing stop
        is what separates this from the naive fixed config — it captures the directional
        move without giving back gains in a reversal.
      </p>

      <h3><code>macro_pulse</code> &middot; Tight, slow, reliable</h3>
      <p>
        Our daily BTC/ETH directional bias (generated by the macro_analyzer cron). Best
        setup: <strong>SL 2%, TP 5%, 24-hour horizon</strong>. 61% win, sharpe 0.41. Small
        sample (n=56) and small per-trade move — useful as a portfolio overlay rather than
        a standalone strategy.
      </p>

      <h3><code>hack</code> &middot; Wide stops, long holds</h3>
      <p>
        Hack/exploit signals. Negative for the affected asset, positive for unaffected. Best
        setup: <strong>no stop, TP 20%, 72-hour horizon</strong>. 43% win rate but average
        winners are large (+2.87% net). Volatile — needs wide stops or no stops to avoid
        being shaken out.
      </p>

      <h3><code>whale</code> &middot; Tight stops, fast holds</h3>
      <p>
        On-chain whale wallet activity. Best setup: <strong>SL 1%, TP 8%, 24-hour horizon</strong>.
        33% win, sharpe 0.24 over 366 trades. The 1% stop is unusually tight but works because
        whale-driven moves either follow through quickly or fail quickly — no slow grinds.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2 id="intel-only">Intel-only signal types</h2>
      <p>
        The following types are <strong>not</strong> in the tradeable set per our
        simulation. We tested 1,728 parameter combinations against each — none flip positive.
        Consume them as context (narrative, positioning, risk awareness), not trade triggers:
      </p>
      <table class="strat-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Type</th><th>n</th><th>Best win %</th><th>Best total $</th><th>Why intel</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><code>regulatory</code></td>
            <td>195</td><td>4.1%</td><td>-$174</td>
            <td>Market front-runs the headline; signals fire after the move</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>macro</code></td>
            <td>40</td><td>12.5%</td><td>-$24</td>
            <td>Diffuse market-wide impact, not single-asset directional</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>other</code></td>
            <td>69</td><td>2.9%</td><td>-$70</td>
            <td>Catch-all bucket — too heterogeneous to trade systematically</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>price</code></td>
            <td>36</td><td>16.7%</td><td>-$2</td>
            <td>Roughly break-even — direction calls don't beat noise</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>
        Two more types — <code>funding</code> (n=12) and <code>liquidation</code> (n=19) — have
        too few samples for a confident verdict. They'll be re-tested as more accumulate.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <code>tradeable_proven</code> set updates from live paper-trade results, so a type
        listed here today could promote into the tradeable set if its forward-test record
        clears the bar. Track changes at <a href="/proof">/proof</a>.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2 id="implementation">Implementing in your bot</h2>
      <p>
        n0brains is a data API. We don't execute trades or hold custody. To act on a signal you'll
        wire the WebSocket or webhook into your own trading layer. Most platforms support every
        execution style we've researched natively:
      </p>
      <table class="strat-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Platform</th><th>Trailing stop</th><th>Time filter</th><th>No-SL</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>TradingView Pine + alerts</td><td>✅</td><td>✅</td><td>✅</td></tr>
          <tr><td>CCXT (Python/Node)</td><td>via library</td><td>via library</td><td>✅</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Hummingbot</td><td>✅</td><td>via strategy</td><td>✅</td></tr>
          <tr><td>3Commas / Cryptohopper</td><td>✅</td><td>limited</td><td>✅</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Hyperliquid SDK direct</td><td>via custom logic</td><td>via custom logic</td><td>✅</td></tr>
          <tr><td>OpenClaw (our agent framework)</td><td>✅</td><td>✅</td><td>✅</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <h3>Example: minimal Python implementation</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Pseudocode — every signal received via WebSocket
async for event in n0brains_ws():
    sig = event["data"]
    if sig["action_hint"] != "trade_signal":
        continue
    if sig["signal_type"] not in {"sentiment", "hack"}:
        continue  # only proven-tradeable types

    asset = sig["asset"]
    direction = sig["direction"]            # "bullish" / "bearish"
    target = sig.get("target_level")        # analytical reference

    # "Ride to horizon" execution example for sentiment:
    # 1. Open position $100, side = direction
    # 2. No SL, no TP
    # 3. Close at +4h
    await place_market(asset, side=direction, size_usd=100)
    await asyncio.sleep(4 * 3600)
    await close_position(asset)`}</code></pre>
      <p>
        Adapt for your venue's trailing-stop primitive, your sizing, and your risk budget. None
        of the above is advice — it's a worked example so you have something to start from.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2 id="proof">Verify the numbers yourself</h2>
      <p>
        Every figure on this page is reproducible from the same data you can access via the API.
        We publish the live paper-trading forward-test at <a href="/proof">/proof</a>; the
        per-signal-type proven-edge statistics are attached to every signal payload under
        <code>type_performance</code>; the methodology is in our backtest scripts.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you find an issue or want a different configuration tested,
        <a href="mailto:support@n0brains.com">email support</a> — we'll run the sweep and
        publish the result.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .legal-card {
    border-left: 3px solid #b13838;
    background: rgba(177, 56, 56, 0.06);
  }
  .legal-card h2 { color: #ef4444; }
  .legal-card strong { color: var(--text-heading); }

  .strat-table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    margin: 0.75rem 0 1rem;
  }
  .strat-table th, .strat-table td {
    padding: 10px 12px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    text-align: left;
  }
  .strat-table th {
    color: var(--text-muted);
    font-weight: 500;
  }
  .strat-table .row-best {
    background: rgba(74, 222, 128, 0.06);
  }
  .strat-table .row-best td:first-child {
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--text-heading);
  }
  .meta {
    color: var(--text-muted);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
  }
</style>
